properties.name: Former Leiter Mine, Zeigler No. 1
properties.description: Posted by Readysubjects  Zeigler, IllinoisBetween 1904 and 1909, the union workers at the coal mines in Zeigler, IL went on strike. They were all evicted from the company town, and the mine itself was turned into a fortress, complete with roof-mounted machine guns, and permanent replacement workers were brought in. The mines exploded twice, under suspicious circumstances, before the owner sold the mine and hired all union workers.

properties.name: Herrin City Cemetery
properties.description: Posted by Readysubjects  Rr 1, Herrin, ILOn the night and early morning of June 21-22, 1920, a group of scab miners were captured and forcibly marched from a mine near Energy, IL several miles to Herrin, where many of the striking miners lived. Many were beaten or shot to death along the way. A few escaped. The six who made it to Herrin, where they were died together and marched to the city cemetery, shot, and their throats slit. The incident shocked the entire country and gave union miners in general, and those in southern Illinois in particular, a particularly violent and bloodthirsty reputation. All the miners who stood trial for the killings were found not guilty.
